Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: Jubilee Holdings, Safaricom Are Active

-- B y   E r i c   O m b o k
-- 
2011-04-01T13:18:57Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-01/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-jubilee-holdings-safaricom-are-active.html
Kenya’s All-Share Index climbed 0. 9
percent to 73.19 by the 3 p.m. close in Nairobi.  Mauritius’s SEMDEX Index added less than 0.1 percent to
2,005.87 by the 1:30 p.m. close in  Port Louis , a 10th day of
increases. The Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share Index  snapped
two days of decreases, adding 0.3 percent to 24,701.64 at 1:36
p.m. in Lagos, while the Ghana Stock Exchange Composite Index
dropped 0.7 percent to 1,063.82 by 12:36 p.m. in Accra.
Namibia’s FTSE/ Namibia Overall Index (FTN098)  gained 0.1 percent to
879.26 at 2:38 p.m. in Windhoek.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan  Africa ,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Jubilee Holdings Ltd. (JBIC)  , a Kenyan  investment
company , climbed 5 shillings, or 2.9 percent, to 180 shillings,
heading for the highest close in a week. Pretax profit for the
year through December surged 84 percent to 2.53 billion
shillings, Chairman Nizar Juma told reporters today in Nairobi,
the capital.  Safaricom Ltd. (SAFCOM)  , East Africa’s biggest mobile-
phone company, snapped three days of declines, rising 5 cents,
or 1.3 percent, to 3.85 shillings, after saying it signed an
agreement with Western Union Co. that enables subscribers to its
money-transfer service to receive funds from 45 countries.  The two companies announced the partnership in an e-mailed
statement yesterday. Safaricom has attracted more than 13.5
million customers since its launch in 2007, and Western Union is
the world’s biggest money-transfer company.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Eric Ombok in Nairobi at 
 eombok@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Gavin Serkin at 
 gserkin@bloomberg.net  